{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568429"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:15:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:15:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20691"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20691"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.21,0.73,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13567"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97522"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13567"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80118"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4470"},{"type":"tags","id":"4473"},{"type":"tags","id":"4475"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32536"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43733"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97522"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the labour ward in active labour with her first child. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. After a prolonged second stage, she has a spontaneous vaginal delivery. The midwife notices significant perineal trauma and calls you to assess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. The uterus is firm and well-contracted. There is moderate vaginal bleeding with an estimated blood loss of 400 mL. You observe a tear extending from the vaginal introitus to the anal margin. The external anal sphincter is 30% torn, but the internal anal sphincter appears intact. There is no visible rectal mucosa. Per rectal examination does not reveal any defect.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most accurate classification of this perineal tear?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["First-degree tear","Second-degree tear","Third-degree tear","Fourth-degree tear"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has sustained a \u003Cstrong\u003Ethird-degree tear\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically a 3a tear. Third-degree perineal tears are defined as injuries that involve the anal sphincter complex. They are further subdivided based on the extent of sphincter involvement: 3a involves less than 50% of the external anal sphincter thickness, 3b involves more than 50% of the external anal sphincter thickness, and 3c involves both the external and internal anal sphincter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncorrect answers:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst-degree tears\u003C/strong\u003E involve only the vaginal mucosa and perineal skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecond-degree tears\u003C/strong\u003E involve the perineal muscles but not the anal sphincter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFourth-degree tears\u003C/strong\u003E involve the anal sphincter complex (external and internal anal sphincters) and the anal epithelium or rectal mucosa. In this case, there is no mention of rectal mucosa involvement, so this classification is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccurate classification of perineal tears is crucial for appropriate management and follow-up. Third-degree tears require repair in an operating theatre under regional or general anaesthesia, performed by an appropriately trained clinician. Follow-up should include pelvic floor physiotherapy and consideration of endoanal ultrasound to assess sphincter integrity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Third-degree perineal tears involve injury to the anal sphincter complex.","Third-degree tears are further classified into 3a, 3b, and 3c based on the extent of external and internal anal sphincter involvement.","Accurate classification of perineal tears is crucial for appropriate management and follow-up."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RCOG). The management of third- and fourth-degree perineal tears. Green-top Guideline No. 29. London: RCOG; 2015. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/media/5jeb5hzu/gtg-29.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80118"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20691"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80118"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-07T15:16:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-07T15:19:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13567"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97522"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"he